My go-to is something like Cuban black beans. Soak 'em overnight and the actual cooking goes faster, but it's not necessary if you're fine with an all day simmer. Don't drain the beans if you do soak. There's a lot of flavor and body in bean juice.

Dice up an onion, mince some garlic, chop a rainbow of sweet peppers, maybe a spoonful of diced chipotles if you're in the mood. You can customize to your liking. Throw it all in the pot with the beans, plenty of water, and some vegetable or chicken broth (I use Better Than Bouillon or bases from the restaurant supply store and mix them straight into the bean juice). Add lots of cumin, a little oregano, some salt, really whatever spices you want. I like the little sazon goya con azafran packets; a couple of those livens things up. Partially cover and simmer until the beans are tender (3-8 hours depending on whether or not you soaked them), replenishing the liquid as necessary. Once the beans are cooked through remove the lid and keep simmering, stirring occasionally, but don't add more liquid as it gets low; you want it to thicken up at this point. Taste and add more seasoning.

You'll end up with delicious, inexpensive, low-fat, high protein slop. Sometimes I'll dump a bag of frozen corn in at the end for more color and flavor. It doesn't sound like much, but I've lived off beans and rice for extended periods and this is my favorite simple way to make a week's worth of meals. Pour over rice and sprinkle with cheese and green onions or cool until thick enough to smear into a burrito or just eat it with a couple runny fried eggs on top. It's all delicious.
